tspan.tspan: In August
2017, the Supreme Court passed
judgement prohibiting triple talaq in India.
The government formulates a bill claiming
100 cases of instant triple talaq after that
judgement.
On 28th December 2017, Law Minister Ravi Shankar
Prasad introduces the bill in the parliament. The bill
proposes to make triple talaq in any form illegal and
void, with up to three years imprisonment for the
husband who pronounces triple talaq.
While the bill is being discussed in the Lok
Sabha, the government issues an ordinance
to make the practice of instant triple talaq
illegal. The ordinance
is cleared by the
President in September
2018. The bill passes
in Lok Sabha on 27th
December 2018.
The bill gets stalled in Rajya Sabha since its
parliamentary sessions get adjourned. The bill
lapses before the elections. An ordinance is
issued again by the President in February 2019.
A fresh bill is introduced on 21st June 2019 and is passed
by
Lok Sabha on 25th July 2019. Rajya Sabha too passes
the
bill on 30th July 2019 and the bill signed into existence
by
the President a day later.
The act becomes retrospectively effective from 19th
September 2018.
The Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Marriage)
or
Triple Talaq Law
